{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"43b09410-697b-4f9a-902c-51497df17128","content":"## Three C# 13 Breaking Changes\n\n### 1. `Buffer.cs` — `[InlineArray]` on `record struct` is now illegal\n\nC# 13 prohibits `[InlineArray]` on record structs because the compiler-synthesized members (Equals, GetHashCode, ToString, PrintMembers) conflict with the inline array layout.\n\n**Fix:** Change `record struct` → `struct`:\n\n```csharp\n[System.Runtime.CompilerServices.InlineArray(10)]\nstruct Buffer\n{\n    private int _element0;\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n### 2. `Generator.cs` — `stackalloc` in local function inside iterator\n\nC# 13 lifts the blanket ban on `unsafe` in iterators/async methods. Side effect: local functions inside iterators now inherit the iterator context. Since `stackalloc` cannot survive across `yield` points, the compiler rejects it in local functions within iterators where it was previously allowed (the local function was treated as separate).\n\n**Fix:** Extract the local function to a standalone private method:\n\n```csharp\nunsafe class DataGenerator\n{\n    IEnumerable<int> Generate()\n    {\n        yield return 1;\n        Process();\n    }\n\n    private static void Process()\n    {\n        int* p = stackalloc int[10];\n        // ... work with pointer\n    }\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n### 3. `Resolver.cs` — Collection expression `[]` overload ambiguity\n\nC# 13 broadened implicit conversions from collection expressions to span types. Now `[]` is convertible to **both** `ReadOnlySpan<int>` and `Span<object>`, making the call ambiguous.\n\n**Fix:** Add an explicit cast to disambiguate:\n\n```csharp\nstatic void Main()\n{\n    Process((ReadOnlySpan<int>)[]);  // explicit target type\n}\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"36cfe8cb-acf2-4df6-8d93-065e752f9ab1","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about C# 13 / .NET 9 breaking changes. Let me analyze each case:\n\n1. **Buffer.cs** - `[InlineArray]` on a `record struct`: C# 13 disallows `[InlineArray]` on record structs. The fix is to change it to a plain `struct`.\n\n2. **Generator.cs** - `stackalloc` in a local function inside an iterator: C# 13 now allows iterators to have `unsafe` code in some contexts, but the rules changed. Actually, let me think more carefully. In C# 12, `stackalloc` was not allowed in iterators at all. \n\nIn C# 13, unsafe code restrictions in iterators were relaxed, but `stackalloc` remains problematic because iterator methods get transformed into state machines where stack-allocated memory can't persist across yield points. Previously in C# 12, local functions within iterators were treated specially and allowed unsafe code since they weren't part of the state machine transformation. C# 13 appears to have tightened these rules around what's permitted in iterator contexts. the local function is now treated as part of the iterator's transformation, so `stackalloc` becomes restricted since it can't safely cross `yield` boundaries—the workaround is to move it into a separate static method. I'm also noticing a change in C# 13's overload resolution for collection expressions, where `[]` now resolves differently with `Span<T>` and `ReadOnlySpan<T>` types compared to C# 12. In C# 13, both `ReadOnlySpan<T>` and `Span<T>` became valid targets for collection expressions, so `[]` can now match either one depending on the overload, creating ambiguity where C# 12 might have resolved to just one. The solution is to explicitly cast the collection expression to the intended span type.\n\nFor the iterator case, C# 13 relaxed restrictions on `unsafe` in iterators, but `stackalloc` still can't be used because the state machine transformation can't preserve stack-allocated memory across yield points—even in local functions that were previously treated as separate from the iterator context. Before C# 13, iterator methods couldn't use `unsafe` at all, so local functions inside them had their own context and could freely use `stackalloc`. Now that `unsafe` is allowed in iterators, the compiler treats local functions as part of the iterator's state machine and applies the same restrictions—meaning `stackalloc` is no longer permitted. The solution is to move the local function out to a separate method.","outputTokens":2208,"requestId":"E03A:3A5014:55C659D:5E22430:69F40135"},"id":"437d5f83-55b8-40b7-a5e2-dd03caebe53c","timestamp":"2026-05-01T01:26:59.570Z","parentId":"7836bf9a-5c9d-4a0d-8b0b-7467cab1d183"}
